  "prompt": "Why do snakes like eating baby chickens?",
  "response": "Snakes are opportunistic feeders, meaning they eat when they have the chance and consume a variety of prey depending on what is available in their environment. Baby chickens, or chicks, are relatively easy for many snakes to catch and consume due to their size and limited ability to defend themselves or escape quickly. \n\nChicks provide a nutritious meal for snakes, as they are rich in protein and other nutrients necessary for the snake\u2019s health. Birds, including chicks, are a natural part of many snake species' diets, especially those that inhabit areas around farms or where wild birds are common.\n\nIt's not necessarily that snakes have a particular preference for baby chickens, but rather that chicks are simply suitable prey when the opportunity arises.",
